title: For Sale:  Pulsar Digisight N750 Digital Night Vision Riflescope
postcontent:
The PULSAR PL76312 N750 DIGISIGHT Riflescope is designed for observation and shooting in twilight and at night-time. This riflescope uses a highly sensitive CCD array (with a range of operation illumination 0.00001 to 30000 lux); the image transmitted to the high resolution display OLED (640 x 480 pixels) is contrasting, crisp, and saturated. Thanks to the OLED display, this riflescope can be used within a wide temperature range from -4 to 122°F (-20 to 50°C) .

The PL76312 Riflescope is a multifunctional device that features several essential options for modern hunting, which includes screen display information on operation status (running time, low battery indicator, active function etc.). The menu has additional functions for image settings: gradual brightness and contrast adjustment, and SumLight signal processing program. The SumLight program automatically increases CCD array sensitivity under low light conditions. The riflescope can be zeroed not only in the traditional manner but also using the new one shot zeroing method. This makes the zeroing procedure significantly faster and more convenient.

This riflescope is equipped with a built-in laser / IR illuminator (780nm wavelength, safety class 1), which considerably increases viewing range. The weaver rail at the side of the body allows an auxiliary IR flashlight to be attached. The basic control functions (switching On / Off the riflescope and the IR illuminator, activation of digital zoom) can be performed with the help of the included wireless remote control. It also features a video output to conduct video recording to external devices without the use of additional adapters and camera or camcorders. If necessary, output video signal standard can be changed from PAL to NTSC.

This riflescope has 1 pre-loaded reticle, but the user can also upload another optional reticle from a reticle base available on the PULSAR website (downloadable). The color of the reticle point can be switched from red to green. The riflescope is resistant to bright light exposure. It can be mounted on a wide range of hunting weapons including those of large calibers (shock resistance is guaranteed if cartridges with muzzle velocity not exceeding 6,000 J are used).
This riflescope operates on 4 rechargeable batteries but can also be powered with an external power supply. External power supplies such as EPS3 or EPS5 (sold separately) prolong the operation time of the riflescope to up to 9 to 20 hours. The IR laser illuminator in this riflescope is fully compliant with US FDA Class 1 laser eye safety requirements.

CASH PRICE IS $1455 CC PRICE IS $1499

title: For Sale:  Limited Edition Winchester 1892 1 of 500 NEW in Box
postcontent:
I am pleased to offer this limited production Winchester Model 1892 chambered in .44 Mag. that is new in the original packaging. Let me reiterate, this is a new 1892- not to be confused with the very common 1894.

The 1892 was made famous in western movies and was the most commonly used model back in the glory days of American Western movies. You'll see a Winchester 1892 in John Wayne's hands in most of his movies. Here's a little history behind the 1892: It was designed by John Browning as a follow up model to the big bore model 1886. Browning was commissioned to design the 1892 by Winchester to meet the need for a modern pistol cartridge repeater with the model 1874 by then nearing obsoleteness. Browning designed the 1892 using essentially the same extremely strong breech locking system of the 1886 but only smaller in stature for shorter rounds vs. the 1886 which was designed around the long and very large 45-70 Govt. cartridge. The 1892 breech locking system is actually considered to be stronger than the 1894 and unlike the 1894 with the 1892, when you actuate the lever down, it doesn't pull the guts of the mechanism half way out. Of course this is a necessary characteristic of the Model 1894 for it to be able to chamber the long 30-30 round but my point is, for a powerful pistol cartridge like the .44 Mag, the Winchester 1892 is just the perfect match. Winchester discontinued the 1892 way back in 1945 but in the last decade Winchester has produced several series of limited editions.

Concerning this specific rifle, when new this rifle retailed for $1,500 and there were only 500 of this octagonal 20" barrel carbine made. The barrel is nicely engraved "LIMITED SERIES - 1 of 500". This particular series of the Model 1892 was offered by Winchester circa 2003 and it's getting rare to find them new in the box . Of those limited editions, I personally believe the octagonal 20" barrel variation is the most desirable and the fact that this one is chambered in the readily available .44 Mag makes it even better. Most of the rifles in this series were chambered in historical rounds like the 38-40 which are more expensive and harder to find. Most dudes bought these as shooters and they are very popular at Cowboy shooting competitions but this one has been a "looker". This rifle was made by Browning's famous Miroku factory in Japan and the fit and finish is nothing less than stunning. The bluing has a high gloss and the walnut stock has attractive figuring in the wood grain with a satin sheen finish. The action is smooth yet tight and the famous compactness of the 1892 makes it just a pleasure to handle this fine rifle.

 Absolutely NO trades- this is a cash sale only.
